Sometimes I feel like my job isn’t important, because I’m not saving lives or changing the world. But the other day, my mom said “I love what you and Whitney do. You help people celebrate their lives and the things they love.” That felt good to hear. Helping people celebrate feels important enough for me. I had never thought of celebration as something quiet that can live on watercolor paper, and I really like that thought. 

This couple asked Whitney and I to paint some of their favorite times together and we had a blast putting this all together. 
.

Another final draft vs first draft from the book. I only have one other first draft panel, because shortly after three not-right illustrations, I put the project down for a year because it wasn’t feeling right and I couldn’t find the visuals in my imagination. During the lockdown in 2020 I dove really intensely into The Artists Way, doing all the morning pages, prompts, and dates. The program encourages indulging your creative kid self. So I finally bought myself an iPad. As it turns out, the iPad was the perfect tool I needed for drafting, so that I could absolutely tear through ideas, revisions, color ideas, character sketches, etc. I drafted the whole book in a few months, and then redid my favorite drafts in watercolor, which took another few months. This panel came more easily, with no drafting except the one shown. 
.
.
.
.
#watercolor

We paint watercolor crests for folks who want them for their branding, for their stationery, for their wedding, or for holiday cards, or to frame as artwork in their house. Sometimes they’re super elaborate, with all kinds of illustrations that give little clues into family history, favorite memories, name meanings, etc. other times, our crests are simple and functional for tiny little applications like stamps or signatures. Simple or elaborate, they’re one of our favorite thing to design, and remind us of the fancy olden days of sealing wax and family crests.

Today I’m in Bavaria, getting more and more distracted by random placards, and thinking about how I’d like to try my hand at a more old fashioned style of calligraphy. The kind my grandma taught me when I was eight, and that I’ve almost completely forgotten how to do. Maybe write the next kids book with it. Maybe start infusing some old world fairytale into my card designs, especially in time for Christmas. We’ll see. 
Anyways, here’s a wedding suite I designed a few years back that I quite like. 🥰

One of the most important people in my childhood was a bantam hen named Herkamer. This is a painting of her flying me up to the afterlife someday. We’re now open for creative commissions! Have a childhood dream, a much-missed pet, a food that embodies your personality, a colorful memory, a hilarious nickname, cool family history? All of these things make for great illustration inspo. We’re ready for some fun projects in 2024! 
#watercolor #illustration

Thankful for the people in my life who have modeled the magic of imagination. This is my grandmother. She was a painter and a calligrapher, she had the imagination of a little kid, and she breathed art into the whole family. I am so deeply thankful for the humans who hold on to art as means of navigating this very strange opportunity we have to live in these very strange bodies on this very strange planet.
